{"title_page": "Robert Gourlay (merchant)", "text_new": "[[File:CHAMBERS(1869) p095 HOUSE OF ROBERT GOURLAY.jpg|thumb|right|'''Robert Gourlay's''' House in Edinburgh before demolition]]\n'''Robert Gourlay''' or '''Robin Gourlaw''' (c. 1530-c. 1600) was a wealthy Edinburgh merchant and Customar of Edinburgh who built a house in Edinburgh (now demolished).\n\n==Life==\nRobert Gourlay is first recorded in the employ of [[Regent Arran]] as a Groom of the Chamber and Wardrobe and was sometime's called the Regent's \"chamber Child\". The Regent bought clothes to wear and a horse to travel with, a maeasure of his importance in the household. In January 1552 he was called \"Keeper of the Wardrobe\".<ref>Melanie Schuessler Bond, ''Dressing the Scottish Court, 1543-1553'' (Boydell: Woodbridge, 2019), pp. 542-3.</ref> Another servant in the Wardrobe, the tailor Malcolm Gourlay was probably his older brother, or uncle.\n\nIn November 1570, as a merchant of Edinburgh, Gourlay supplied two hanks of gold thread to the Edinburgh tailor James Inglis and embroiderer John Young, for clothes for [[James VI of Scotland]].<ref>Charles Thorpe McInnes, ''Accounts of the Treasurer of Scotland: 1566-1574'', vol. 12 (HMSO: Edinburgh, 1970), pp. 227-8.</ref>\n\n[[Regent Morton]] was a friend of Robert Gourlay, and allowed him to export grain, despite shortages. Gourlay was an elder of Edinburgh Kirk. In May 1574 the Kirk censured him for exporting grain and he was compelled to appear in [[St Giles' Cathedral|St Giles Kirk]] at the \"marriage place\" wearing his best gown, which he was ordered to sell for the benefit of the poor.<ref>[[Robert Chambers (publisher, born 1802)|Robert Chambers]], [https://archive.org/details/domesticannalsof01chamiala/page/94 ''Domestic annals of Scotland, from the Reformation to the Revolution'', vol. 1 (Edinburgh, 1858), p. 94:] [https://archive.org/details/miscellanyedbya00clubgoog/page/n118 ''Maitland Miscellany'', vol. 1 (Edinburgh, 1833), pp. 101-102.]</ref> The Regent tried to insist to the minister Mr James Lawson that Gourlay should not be punished, and publicly declared he had allowed Gourlay to export cereals despite the scarcity.<ref>[[Thomas Thomson (advocate)|Thomas Thomson]], ''Calderwood's History of the Kirk of Scotland'', vol. 3 (Edinburgh, 1843), p. 328.</ref> The English ambassador in Edinburgh [[Henry Killigrew (diplomat)|Henry Killigrew]] sent news of the incident to [[Francis Walsingham]] saying that it caused \"some little grudging\" and \"unkindness\" between the Kirk and Regent Morton.<ref>William K. Boyd, ''Calendar State Papers Scotland: 1571-1574'', vol. 4 (Edinburgh, 1905), pp. 680-1 no. 788.</ref> However, the historian [[Michael Lynch (historian)|Michael Lynch]] however suggests the affair did not cause a significant rift between Morton and the clergy.<ref>Michael Lynch, ''Edinburgh and the Reformation'' (John Donald: Edinburgh, 1981), pp. 153, 167.</ref>\n\nAs \"Customar-General\" of Edinburgh from 22 December 1573, Gourlay collected export and import customs and tolls due to the crown in Edinburgh.<ref>[[Gordon Donaldson]], ''Register of the Privy Seal of Scotland: 1567-1574'', vol 6 (HMSO: Edinburgh, 1963), p. 424 no. 2247.</ref>  He was exempt from tax, and complained to the [[Privy Council of Scotland]] when he was made to contribute \u00a330 [[pounds Scots|Scots]] to the Burgh fund for the [[Entry of James VI into Edinburgh]] in 1579. In December 1582 he undertook to pay several royal debts to Edinburgh merchants totalling 550 French gold \"[[\u00c9cu|crowns of the sun]]\" out of the towns customs.<ref>David Masson, ''Register of the Privy Council of Scotland: 1578-1585'', vol. 3 (Edinburgh, 1880), pp. 259-260, 530, 538.</ref>\n\nHe also supplied silver to the mint. In September and October 1580 Robert Gourlay and Master John Provand supplied silver worth \u00a378-7s-8d. Scots to the mint in Edinburgh to be coined. They were paid a further \u00a32,123-7s-8d. outstanding for silver supplied by them.<ref>Charles Thorpe McInnes, ''Accounts of the Treasurer of Scotland: 1574-1580'', vol 13 (Edinburgh: HMSO, 1978), pp. 410, 412.</ref>\n\nGourlay married Helen Cruik.\n\n==Robert Gourlay's House==\nThe house was built on the [[Royal Mile]] on the south side of the Lawnmarket on lands and vacant lots, known as \"waste\", belonging to Gourlay and Helen Cruik and partly over an old lane called \"Mauchan's Close\". The earliest date marker on the house was \"1569\" carved in stone. James VI allowed the right of Robert Gourlay and Helen Cruik to have blocked Mauchan's close with a wall or \"dyke\" in 1588 and 1589. In later years the \"Old Bank\" or \"[[Bank of Scotland]]\" occupied the site until 1805. The entry became known as \"Old Bank Close\". Robert Gourlay's House was demolished in 1834.<ref>[[Daniel Wilson (academic)|Daniel Wilson]], [https://archive.org/details/memorialsedinbu02wilsgoog/page/n324 ''Memorials of Edinburgh in the Olden Time'', vol. 1 (Edinburgh, 1891), pp. 223-4.]</ref>\n\nIn 1637 Robert Gourlay's grandson David Gourlay (d. 25 December 1644) sold the house to the lawyer [[Sir Thomas Hope, 1st Baronet|Sir Thomas Hope of Craighall]].<ref>Daniel Wilson, ''Memorials of Edinburgh in the Olden Time'', vol. 1 (Edinburgh, 1891), pp. 229-230.</ref> Sir Thomas Hope bought the house for his son, Sir [[Thomas Hope of Kerse]] who lived there with his wife Helen Rae and their family until his death on 23 August 1644.<ref>[https://archive.org/details/diaryofpubliccor76hopeuoft/page/122 ''A Diary of the Public Correspondence of Sir Thomas Hope of Craighall, 1633\u20131645: From the Original, in the Library at Pinkie House'' (Bannatyne Club: Edinburgh, 1843), p. 123.].</ref>\n\n===Prisoners in Robert Gourlay's House===\nSir [[William Drury]] stayed in the house during the 'lang siege' of [[Edinburgh Castle]] in 1573. After the castle surrendered Sir [[William Kirkcaldy of Grange]], his wife Margaret Learmonth, his brother, [[Alexander Home, 5th Lord Home]], [[William Maitland of Lethington]], his wife [[Mary Fleming]] the Lady Lethington, Sir John Wishart of Pitarrow, and the [[Archibald Campbell, 5th Earl of Argyll|Countess of Argyll, Janet Cunningham]] were taken to the house as prisoners.<ref>Daniel Wilson, ''Memorials of Edinburgh in the Olden Time'', vol. 1 (Edinburgh, 1891), p. 226.</ref>\n\nWhen Regent Morton was arrested in May 1581 he was first imprisoned in Robert Gourlay's house.<ref>Robert Chambers, [https://archive.org/details/domesticannalsof01chamiala/page/144 ''Domestic annals of Scotland, from the Reformation to the Revolution'', vol. 1 (Edinburgh, 1858), p. 144.]</ref>\n\nIn June 1588 [[John Maxwell, 8th Lord Maxwell]] was held in the house as the prisoner of Sir [[William Stewart of Monkton]]. Monkton was killed by [[Francis Stewart, 5th Earl of Bothwell]] in Blackfriars Wynd a week later. During the uproar Maxwell tried to get away but was caught by the [[Lord Provost of Edinburgh|Provost of Edinburgh]], [[Sir John Arnot|John Arnot]].<ref>David Masson, ''Register of the Privy Council of Scotland: 1585-1592'' vol. 4 (Edinburgh, 1881), pp. 292-3 fn: Daniel Wilson, ''Memorials of Edinburgh in the Olden Time'', vol. 1 (Edinburgh, 1891), p. 227-8.</ref>\n\nColonel William Sempill, an agent of the Spanish empire, was to be held in the house in August 1588 but escaped on the first night from a window using a rope smuggled in by his mother.<ref>David Masson, ''Register of the Privy Council of Scotland: 1585-1592'' vol. 4 (Edinburgh, 1881), pp. 316 fn., 821.</ref> In another version of the escape story, Sempill's sister, [[James Ross, 4th Lord Ross|Jean, Lady Ross]], bought him a silk rope baked in a pie. Sempill escaped while his guards were eating two other pies brought by Jean Sempill. He reached the [[Grassmarket]] and evaded soldiers by pretending to be drunk.<ref>William Forbes-Leith, [https://archive.org/details/narrativesscotti00unknuoft/page/n383 ''Narratives of Scottish Catholics under Mary Stuart and James VI'' (London, 1889), p. 369.]</ref>\n\n[[James VI of Scotland]] found it convenient to lodge in the house on several occasions, rather than stay at [[Holyrood Palace]]. He was there on 3 April 1594.<ref>John W. Mackenzie, ''A Chronicle of the Kings of Scotland'' (Edinburgh, 1830), p. 149.</ref>\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n* [https://www.nationalgalleries.org/art-and-artists/6355/robert-gourlays-house-old-bank-close-edinburgh Painting of 'Robert Gourlay's House, Old Bank Close, Edinburgh', National Galleries of Scotland]\n* [https://canmore.org.uk/site/112242/edinburgh-298-300-lawnmarket-old-bank-close-robert-gourlays-house 'Edinburgh, 298-300 Lawnmarket, Old Bank Close, Robert Gourlay's House', Historic Environment Scotland: Canmore]\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Gourlay, Robert}}\n[[Category:History of Edinburgh]]\n[[Category:16th-century Scottish people]]\n[[Category:Year of birth unknown]]\n[[Category:Scottish merchants]]\n[[Category:Old Town, Edinburgh]]\n[[Category:People from Edinburgh]]\n[[Category:Year of birth uncertain]]\n", "text_old": "[[File:CHAMBERS(1869) p095 HOUSE OF ROBERT GOURLAY.jpg|thumb|right|'''Robert Gourlay's''' House in Edinburgh before demolition]]\n'''Robert Gourlay''' or '''Robin Gourlaw''' (c. 1530-c.1600) was a wealthy Edinburgh merchant and Customar of Edinburgh, and built a house in Edinburgh now demolished.\n==Life==\nRobert Gourlay is first recorded in the employ of [[Regent Arran]] as a Groom of the Chamber and Wardrobe and was sometime's called the Regent's \"chamber Child\". The Regent bought clothes to wear and a horse to travel with, a maeasure of his importance in the household. In January 1552 he was called \"Keeper of the Wardrobe\".<ref>Melanie Schuessler Bond, ''Dressing the Scottish Court, 1543-1553'' (Boydell: Woodbridge, 2019), pp. 542-3.</ref> Another servant in the Wardrobe, the tailor Malcolm Gourlay was probably his older brother, or uncle. \n\nIn November 1570, as a merchant of Edinburgh, Gourlay supplied two hanks of gold thread to the Edinburgh tailor James Inglis and embroiderer John Young, for clothes for [[James VI of Scotland]].<ref>Charles Thorpe McInnes, ''Accounts of the Treasurer of Scotland: 1566-1574'', vol. 12 (HMSO: Edinburgh, 1970), pp. 227-8.</ref>\n\n[[Regent Morton]] was a friend of Robert Gourlay, and allowed him to export grain, despite shortages. Gourlay was an elder of Edinburgh Kirk. In May 1574 the Kirk censured him for exporting grain and he was compelled to appear in [[St Giles' Cathedral|St Giles Kirk]] at the \"marriage place\" wearing his best gown, which he was ordered to sell for the benefit of the poor.<ref>[[Robert Chambers (publisher, born 1802)|Robert Chambers]], [https://archive.org/details/domesticannalsof01chamiala/page/94 ''Domestic annals of Scotland, from the Reformation to the Revolution'', vol. 1 (Edinburgh, 1858), p. 94:] [https://archive.org/details/miscellanyedbya00clubgoog/page/n118 ''Maitland Miscellany'', vol. 1 (Edinburgh, 1833), pp. 101-102.]</ref> The Regent tried to insist to the minister Mr James Lawson that Gourlay should not be punished, and publicly declared he had allowed Gourlay to export cereals despite the scarcity.<ref>[[Thomas Thomson (advocate)|Thomas Thomson]], ''Calderwood's History of the Kirk of Scotland'', vol. 3 (Edinburgh, 1843), p. 328.</ref> The English ambassador in Edinburgh [[Henry Killigrew (diplomat)|Henry Killigrew]] sent news of the incident to [[Francis Walsingham]] saying that it caused \"some little grudging\" and \"unkindness\" between the Kirk and Regent Morton.<ref>William K. Boyd, ''Calendar State Papers Scotland: 1571-1574'', vol. 4 (Edinburgh, 1905), pp. 680-1 no. 788.</ref> However, the historian [[Michael Lynch (historian)|Michael Lynch]] however suggests the affair did not cause a significant rift between Morton and the clergy.<ref>Michael Lynch, ''Edinburgh and the Reformation'' (John Donald: Edinburgh, 1981), pp. 153, 167.</ref>\n\nAs \"Customar-General\" of Edinburgh from 22 December 1573, Gourlay collected export and import customs and tolls due to the crown in Edinburgh.<ref>[[Gordon Donaldson]], ''Register of the Privy Seal of Scotland: 1567-1574'', vol 6 (HMSO: Edinburgh, 1963), p. 424 no. 2247.</ref>  He was exempt from tax, and complained to the [[Privy Council of Scotland]] when he was made to contribute \u00a330 [[pounds Scots|Scots]] to the Burgh fund for the [[Entry of James VI into Edinburgh]] in 1579. In December 1582 he undertook to pay several royal debts to Edinburgh merchants totalling 550 French gold \"[[\u00c9cu|crowns of the sun]]\" out of the towns customs.<ref>David Masson, ''Register of the Privy Council of Scotland: 1578-1585'', vol. 3 (Edinburgh, 1880), pp. 259-260, 530, 538.</ref> \n\nHe also supplied silver to the mint. In September and October 1580 Robert Gourlay and Master John Provand supplied silver worth \u00a378-7s-8d. Scots to the mint in Edinburgh to be coined. They were paid a further \u00a32,123-7s-8d. outstanding for silver supplied by them.<ref>Charles Thorpe McInnes, ''Accounts of the Treasurer of Scotland: 1574-1580'', vol 13 (Edinburgh: HMSO, 1978), pp. 410, 412.</ref>\n\nGourlay married Helen Cruik.\n\n==Robert Gourlay's House==\nThe house was built on the [[Royal Mile]] on the south side of the Lawnmarket on lands and vacant lots, known as \"waste\", belonging to Gourlay and Helen Cruik and partly over an old lane called \"Mauchan's Close\". The earliest date marker on the house was \"1569\" carved in stone. James VI allowed the right of Robert Gourlay and Helen Cruik to have blocked Mauchan's close with a wall or \"dyke\" in 1588 and 1589. In later years the \"Old Bank\" or \"[[Bank of Scotland]]\" occupied the site until 1805. The entry became known as \"Old Bank Close\". Robert Gourlay's House was demolished in 1834.<ref>[[Daniel Wilson (academic)|Daniel Wilson]], [https://archive.org/details/memorialsedinbu02wilsgoog/page/n324 ''Memorials of Edinburgh in the Olden Time'', vol. 1 (Edinburgh, 1891), pp. 223-4.]</ref>\n\nIn 1637 Robert Gourlay's grandson David Gourlay (d. 25 December 1644) sold the house to the lawyer [[Sir Thomas Hope, 1st Baronet|Sir Thomas Hope of Craighall]].<ref>Daniel Wilson, ''Memorials of Edinburgh in the Olden Time'', vol. 1 (Edinburgh, 1891), pp. 229-230.</ref> Sir Thomas Hope bought the house for his son, Sir [[Thomas Hope of Kerse]] who lived there with his wife Helen Rae and their family until his death on 23 August 1644.<ref>[https://archive.org/details/diaryofpubliccor76hopeuoft/page/122 ''A Diary of the Public Correspondence of Sir Thomas Hope of Craighall, 1633\u20131645: From the Original, in the Library at Pinkie House'' (Bannatyne Club: Edinburgh, 1843), p. 123.].</ref>\n\n===Prisoners in Robert Gourlay's House===\nSir [[William Drury]] stayed in the house during the 'lang siege' of [[Edinburgh Castle]] in 1573. After the castle surrendered Sir [[William Kirkcaldy of Grange]], his wife Margaret Learmonth, his brother, [[Alexander Home, 5th Lord Home]], [[William Maitland of Lethington]], his wife [[Mary Fleming]] the Lady Lethington, Sir John Wishart of Pitarrow, and the [[Archibald Campbell, 5th Earl of Argyll|Countess of Argyll, Janet Cunningham]] were taken to the house as prisoners.<ref>Daniel Wilson, ''Memorials of Edinburgh in the Olden Time'', vol. 1 (Edinburgh, 1891), p. 226.</ref>\n\nWhen Regent Morton was arrested in May 1581 he was first imprisoned in Robert Gourlay's house.<ref>Robert Chambers, [https://archive.org/details/domesticannalsof01chamiala/page/144 ''Domestic annals of Scotland, from the Reformation to the Revolution'', vol. 1 (Edinburgh, 1858), p. 144.]</ref>\n\nIn June 1588 [[John Maxwell, 8th Lord Maxwell]] was held in the house as the prisoner of Sir [[William Stewart of Monkton]]. Monkton was killed by [[Francis Stewart, 5th Earl of Bothwell]] in Blackfriars Wynd a week later. During the uproar Maxwell tried to get away but was caught by the [[Lord Provost of Edinburgh|Provost of Edinburgh]], [[Sir John Arnot|John Arnot]].<ref>David Masson, ''Register of the Privy Council of Scotland: 1585-1592'' vol. 4 (Edinburgh, 1881), pp. 292-3 fn: Daniel Wilson, ''Memorials of Edinburgh in the Olden Time'', vol. 1 (Edinburgh, 1891), p. 227-8.</ref>\n\nColonel William Sempill, an agent of the Spanish empire, was to be held in the house in August 1588 but escaped on the first night from a window using a rope smuggled in by his mother.<ref>David Masson, ''Register of the Privy Council of Scotland: 1585-1592'' vol. 4 (Edinburgh, 1881), pp. 316 fn., 821.</ref> In another version of the escape story, Sempill's sister, [[James Ross, 4th Lord Ross|Jean, Lady Ross]], bought him a silk rope baked in a pie. Sempill escaped while his guards were eating two other pies brought by Jean Sempill. He reached the [[Grassmarket]] and evaded soldiers by pretending to be drunk.<ref>William Forbes-Leith, [https://archive.org/details/narrativesscotti00unknuoft/page/n383 ''Narratives of Scottish Catholics under Mary Stuart and James VI'' (London, 1889), p. 369.]</ref>\n\n[[James VI of Scotland]] found it convenient to lodge in the house on several occassions, rather than stay at [[Holyrood Palace]]. He was there on 3 April 1594.<ref>John W. Mackenzie, ''A Chronicle of the Kings of Scotland'' (Edinburgh, 1830), p. 149.</ref>\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n* [https://www.nationalgalleries.org/art-and-artists/6355/robert-gourlays-house-old-bank-close-edinburgh Painting of 'Robert Gourlay's House, Old Bank Close, Edinburgh', National Galleries of Scotland]\n* [https://canmore.org.uk/site/112242/edinburgh-298-300-lawnmarket-old-bank-close-robert-gourlays-house 'Edinburgh, 298-300 Lawnmarket, Old Bank Close, Robert Gourlay's House', Historic Environment Scotland: Canmore]\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Gourlay, Robert}}\n[[Category:History of Edinburgh]]\n[[Category:16th-century Scottish people]]\n[[Category:Year of birth unknown]]\n[[Category:Scottish merchants]]\n[[Category:Old Town, Edinburgh]]\n[[Category:People from Edinburgh]]\n", "name_user": "JHunterJ", "label": "safe", "comment": "clean up,typo(s) fixed: occassions \u2192 occasions", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Robert_Gourlay_(merchant)"}
{"title_page": "Fidel Escobar", "text_new": "{{spanish name 2|Escobar|Mendieta}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=June 2018}}\n{{Infobox football biography\n|name           = Fidel Escobar\n|image          = ENG-PAN (13) (cropped) 2.jpg\n|image_size     = 200\n|caption        = Escobar lining up for [[Panama national football team|Panama]] at the [[2018 FIFA World Cup]]\n|fullname       = Fidel Escobar Mendieta\n|birth_date     = {{birth date and age|df=yes|1995|1|9}}\n|birth_place    = [[Panama City]], Panama\n|height         = 1.82 m<ref>{{cite web|url=https://tournament.fifadata.com/documents/FWC/2018/pdf/FWC_2018_SQUADLISTS.PDF|title=2018 FIFA World Cup: List of players|publisher=FIFA|format=PDF|page=20|date=8 July 2018}}</ref>\n|position       = [[Defender (association football)|Centre back]]\n|currentclub    = [[C\u00f3rdoba CF|C\u00f3rdoba]]<br/>(on loan from [[Sporting San Miguelito|San Miguelito]])\n|clubnumber     = 18\n|years1         = 2012\u20132013 |clubs1 = [[San Francisco F.C.|San Francisco]]     | caps1 = 16 | goals1 = 1\n|years2         = 2014\u2013     |clubs2 = [[Sporting San Miguelito|San Miguelito]] | caps2 = 65 | goals2 = 6\n|years3         = 2016\u20132017 |clubs3 = \u2192 [[Sporting CP B|Sporting B]] (loan)    | caps3 = 14 | goals3 = 0\n|years4         = 2017\u20132018 |clubs4 = \u2192 [[New York Red Bulls]] (loan)          | caps4 = 12 | goals4 = 0\n|years5         = 2017\u20132018 |clubs5 = \u2192 [[New York Red Bulls II]] (loan)       | caps5 = 6  | goals5 = 1\n|years6         = 2019      |clubs6 = \u2192 [[Correcaminos UAT]] (loan)            | caps6 = 0  | goals6 = 0\n|years7         = 2019\u2013     |clubs7 = \u2192 [[C\u00f3rdoba CF|C\u00f3rdoba]] (loan)          | caps7 = 0  | goals7 = 0\n|nationalyears1 = 2015  | nationalteam1 = [[Panama national under-20 football team|Panama U20]] | nationalcaps1  = 7 | nationalgoals1 = 3\n|nationalyears2 = 2015\u2013 | nationalteam2 = [[Panama national football team|Panama]]              | nationalcaps2  = 42 | nationalgoals2 = 1\n|pcupdate       = 23:59, 15 May 2019 (UTC)\n|ntupdate       = 23:59, 4 November 2019 (UTC)\n}}\n'''Fidel Escobar Mendieta''' (born 9 January 1995) is a Panamanian [[Association football|footballer]] who plays as a [[Defender (association football)|central defender]] for Spanish club [[C\u00f3rdoba CF]], on loan from [[Sporting San Miguelito]], and the [[Panama national football team]].\n\n==Club career==\n===San Francisco===\nBorn in [[Panama City]], Escobar graduated from [[San Francisco F.C.|San Francisco]]'s youth setup, and made his senior debut during the 2012\u201313 campaign, aged only 18. During the next season he established himself as a first team regular making 14 starts and scoring one goal. On 26 October 2013, Escobar scored his first goal for ''Los Monjes'' in a 2\u20130 victory over [[Chorrillo F.C.|Chorrillo]].<ref>{{cite web|title=Chepo y San Francisco creen en las semifinales\n|url=http://lpf.com.pa/w/chepo-y-san-francisco-creen-en-las-semifinales/|website=lpf.com.pa|accessdate=27 October 2013|language=es}}</ref>\n\n===Sporting San Miguelito===\nAfter impressing with San Francisco, Escobar was signed by [[Sporting San Miguelito]] for the 2014 Clausura season. He made 14 appearances scoring one goal in his first season at the club. On 16 March 2014, Escobar scored his first goal with San Miguelito in a 2\u20132 draw with [[Alianza F.C. (Panama)|Alianza]].<ref>{{cite web|title=Chorrillo es l\u00edder tras 11 jornadas completas\n|url=http://lpf.com.pa/w/chorrillo-es-lider-tras-11-jornadas-completas/|website=lpf.com.pa|accessdate=14 March 2014|language=es}}</ref> In his two and a half seasons with the club Escobar made 65 league appearances scoring six goals.\n\n====Sporting B (loan)====\nAs a result of his impressive play with his club and at the Under-20 World Cup Escobar received the attention of European clubs. During July 2016, Escobar was sent on loan with an option to buy to [[Sporting Clube de Portugal]]'s reserve side [[Sporting CP B|Sporting B]].<ref>{{cite web|title=Sporting: Fidel Escobar est\u00e1 a caminho de Lisboa\n|url=http://www.maisfutebol.iol.pt/liga/05-07-2016/sporting-fidel-escobar-esta-a-caminho-de-lisboa|website=maisfutebol.iol.pt|accessdate=5 July 2016|language=pt}}</ref> Escobar made his debut for Sporting B on 6 August 2016 playing the entire match in a 1\u20132 loss to [[Portimonense S.C.]].<ref>{{cite web|title=\nSPORTING B-PORTIMONENSE, 1-2: PIRES BISA NA REVIRAVOLTA ALGARVIA\n|url=http://www.record.pt/futebol/futebol-nacional/2--liga/detalhe/sporting-b-portimonense-1-2-pires-bisa-na-reviravolta-algarvia.html|website=record.pt|accessdate=6 August 2016|language=pt}}</ref> In January 2017, Escobar attempted to terminate his contract with Sporting in search of other opportunities and was threatened with legal action by the Portuguese side.<ref>{{cite web|title=Sporting: Fidel no quiere volver a Lisboa|url=http://futbolcentroamerica.com/5762/fidel-escobar-no-quiere-regresar-a-sporting-de-lisboa-y-pide-rescindir|website=futbolcentroamerica.com|accessdate=12 January 2017|language=es|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170906232117/http://futbolcentroamerica.com/5762/fidel-escobar-no-quiere-regresar-a-sporting-de-lisboa-y-pide-rescindir|archive-date=6 September 2017|url-status=dead}}</ref> Escobar eventually apologized to the club and was reinstated for the second half of the season. He made his return to the side on 15 April 2017, starting in a 2\u20130 victory over [[Uni\u00e3o da Madeira]].<ref>{{cite web|title=\nSPORTING B-UNI\u00c3O DA MADEIRA, 2-0: LE\u00d5ES REGRESSAM \u00c0S VIT\u00d3RIAS\n|url=http://www.record.pt/futebol/futebol-nacional/2--liga/detalhe/sporting-b-uniao-da-madeira-2-0-leoes-regressam-as-vitorias.html|website=record.pt|accessdate=15 April 2017|language=pt}}</ref>\n\n====New York Red Bulls (loan)====\nOn 27 July 2017 it was announced that Escobar was joining [[New York Red Bulls]] on an 18-month loan.<ref>{{cite web|title=New York Red Bulls Add Panama International Fidel Escobar on Loan\n|url=https://www.newyorkredbulls.com/post/2017/07/27/new-york-red-bulls-add-panama-international-fidel-escobar-loan|website=newyorkredbulls.com|accessdate=27 July 2017}}</ref> For his play on 10 March 2018, in which he helped lead New York to a 4\u20130 victory over [[Portland Timbers]] in the team's first league match of the season, Escobar was named to the Starting XI for Major League Soccer's Team of the Week.<ref>{{cite web|title=Fidel Escobar in Starting XI for Team of the Week presented by Audi\n|url=https://www.newyorkredbulls.com/post/2018/03/12/fidel-escobar-starting-xi-team-week-presented-audi-sean-davis-carlos-rivas-bench|website=newyorkredbulls.com|accessdate=12 March 2018}}</ref>\n\nEscobar was loaned to affiliate side [[New York Red Bulls II]] of the [[United Soccer League]] for the match against [[Tampa Bay Rowdies]] on 14 April 2018. He opened the scoring for New York in the 5\u20130 victory.<ref>{{cite web|title=Red Bulls II Romp Past Rowdies|url=https://www.uslsoccer.com/news_article/show/907855?referrer_id=2424350|website=uslsoccer.com|accessdate=14 April 2018}}</ref>\n\nEscobar's loan was not extended by the Red Bulls at the end of their 2018 season.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.newyorkredbulls.com/post/2018/12/04/new-york-red-bulls-announce-end-season-roster-updates|title=New York Red Bulls Announce End of Season Roster Updates|work=NewYorkRedBulls.com}}</ref>\n\n====C\u00f3rdoba (loan)====\nOn 10 July 2019, after a six-month spell at [[Correcaminos UAT]], Escobar joined Spanish [[Segunda Divisi\u00f3n B]] side [[C\u00f3rdoba CF]] on loan for one year.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.cordobacf.com/noticia/fidel-escobar-tercer-fichaje-del-cordoba-cf|title=Fidel Escobar, tercer fichaje del C\u00f3rdoba CF|trans-title=Fidel Escobar, third signing of C\u00f3rdoba CF|publisher=C\u00f3rdoba CF|language=es|date=10 July 2019|accessdate=16 August 2019}}</ref>\n\n==International career==\nEscobar played at the [[2015 FIFA U-20 World Cup]] in [[New Zealand]].<ref>{{FIFA player|385030}}</ref> He made his debut in the competition on 30 May 2015 scoring an 84th-minute equalizer in a 2\u20132 draw against heavily favored side [[Argentina national under-20 football team|Argentina]].<ref>{{cite web|title=Argentina empat\u00f3 con Panam\u00e1 en el debut del Mundial Sub-20\n|url=http://www.lanacion.com.ar/1797351-argentina-empato-con-panama-en-el-debut-del-mundial-sub-20|website=lanacion.com.ar|accessdate=30 May 2015|language=es}}</ref>\n\nEscobar made his senior debut for [[Panama national football team|Panama]] in a February 2015 [[friendly match]] against the [[United States men's national soccer team|United States]].\n\nIn May 2018 he was named in Panama\u2019s preliminary 35 man [[Panama national football team|squad]] for the [[2018 FIFA World Cup]] in Russia, and played all three matches in an eventual group-stage exit.<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://www.goal.com/en-gb/amp/news/revealed-every-world-cup-2018-squad-23-man-preliminary-lists/oa0atsduflsv1nsf6oqk576rb|title=Revealed: Every World Cup 2018 squad - Final 23-man lists {{!}} Goal.com|access-date=5 June 2018}}</ref>\n\n==Career statistics==\n===Club===\n{{updated|28 October 2018}}<ref>{{Soccerway|fidel-escobar/294835|accessdate=18 July 2018}}</ref>\n{| class=\"wikitable\" style=\"text-align: center;\"\n|-\n!rowspan=\"2\"|Club\n!rowspan=\"2\"|Season\n!colspan=\"3\"|League\n!colspan=\"2\"|Cup\n!colspan=\"2\"|Continental\n!colspan=\"2\"|Other\n!colspan=\"2\"|Total\n|-\n!Division!!Apps!!Goals!!Apps!!Goals!!Apps!!Goals!!Apps!!Goals!!Apps!!Goals\n|-\n|rowspan=\"3\"|[[San Francisco F.C.|San Francisco]]\n|[[2012\u201313 Liga Paname\u00f1a de F\u00fatbol season|2012\u201313]]\n|rowspan=\"2\"|[[Liga Paname\u00f1a de F\u00fatbol]]\n|2||0||colspan=\"2\"|\u2014||colspan=\"2\"|\u2014||colspan=\"2\"|\u2014||2||0\n|-\n|[[2013\u201314 Liga Paname\u00f1a de F\u00fatbol season|2013\u201314]]\n|14||1||colspan=\"2\"|\u2014||colspan=\"