{"title_page": "Planned French invasion of Britain (1708)", "text_new": "{{Infobox military conflict\n| conflict    = Planned French Invasion of Britain, 1708\n| partof      = [[Jacobite risings]]\n| image       = File:Jacobite broadside - Coloured portrait of Prince James as young man1.jpg\n| image_size  = 225px\n| caption     = [[James Francis Edward Stuart]] ca 1708\n| date        = March 1708\n| place       = Great Britain\n| result      = Decisive British government victory\n| combatant1  = [[Jacobitism|Jacobites]] <br /> {{flagcountry|Kingdom of France}}\n| combatant2  = {{flagcountry|Kingdom of Great Britain}}\n| commander1  = {{flagicon|Kingdom of France}}[[Claude de Forbin]]<br /> {{flagicon|Kingdom of France}} [[Charles-Auguste de Goyon|Comte de Gac\u00e9]]\n| commander2  = {{flagicon|Kingdom of Great Britain}} [[George Byng, 1st Viscount Torrington|Sir George Byng]] <br /> {{flagicon|Kingdom of Great Britain}} Rear Admiral Baker\n| campaignbox={{Campaignbox Jacobite risings}}\n}}\nThe '''Planned French Invasion of Britain, 1708,''' also known as the ''''Entreprise d\u2019\u00c9cosse,'''' took place during the [[War of the Spanish Succession]]. The French planned to land 5,000-6,000 soldiers in North-East [[Scotland]] to support a rising by local [[Jacobitism|Jacobites]], that would restore [[James Francis Edward Stuart]] to the throne of Great Britain. \n\nDespite French commander [[Claude de Forbin]] warning the chances of evading the [[Royal Navy]] long enough to land his troops were extremely limited, his fleet of small [[privateers]] reached Scotland in March 1708. As he had forecast, he was unable to disembark the troops and returned home, narrowly escaping a pursuing British naval force.\n\nSuch attempts reflected a fundamental and continuing divergence of objectives; while the Stuarts wanted to regain their throne, for the French, they were a simple and low-cost way to absorb British resources. Much of the [[Royal Navy]] was occupied chasing de Forbin, while troops were diverted from Ireland and Southern England. This made it successful for France, but a failure for the Jacobites. \n\n==Background==\n{{Main|War of the Spanish Succession}}\n[[File:Claude de Forbin.jpg|thumb|left|French Admiral [[Claude de Forbin]] (1656-1733); he had little faith in the expedition from the start]]\nUnder the 1697 [[Treaty of Ryswick]], [[Louis XIV]] withdrew support from the exiled [[James II]], and recognised [[William III of England|William III]] as legitimate monarch. However, when James died on 16 September 1701, he reneged on this, and proclaimed his son [[James Francis Edward Stuart]] King of England and Scotland. The [[War of the Spanish Succession]] began soon after; William died in March 1702 and was succeeded by the last Stuart monarch, James' Protestant daughter [[Anne, Queen of Great Britain|Anne]].{{sfn|Williams|1960|p=340}}\n\nBy the end of 1707, the war had reached stalemate; despite victories in [[Flanders]], the Allies had been unable to break French border defences, or place their candidate on the Spanish throne. Both sides attempted to use internal conflicts to break the deadlock; Britain supported the [[Camisard|Camisard rebels]] in South-West France, with the Jacobites serving a similar function for the French.{{sfn|Owen|1938|p=238}}\n\nJacobite agent [[Nathaniel Hooke (Jacobite)|Nathaniel Hooke]] convinced Louis there was an opportunity for a Scottish rising, which would divert British troops from Europe. The [[Acts of Union 1707|1707 Act of Union]] was widely unpopular in Scotland, while French [[privateer]]s caused enormous losses for their maritime trade, and the coastal fishing industry.{{sfn|Whatley|2011|p=55}} Protecting Scottish shipping was not a priority for the [[Royal Navy]], which faced multiple demands on its resources for escorting merchant convoys.{{sfn|Journal of the House of Lords|1708|pp=405\u2013423}}\n\nHooke visited Scotland in 1707, meeting supporters like the [[Charles Hay, 13th Earl of Erroll|Earl of Erroll]], while elderly Jacobite [[Thomas Buchan]] provided reports on bases at [[Fort William, Highland|Fort William]] and [[Inverness]].{{sfn|Hopkins|2004}} Senior nobles like the Dukes of [[John_Murray,_1st_Duke_of_Atholl|Atholl]] and [[James Hamilton, 4th Duke of Hamilton|Hamilton]] refused to commit, partly due to an attempt in 1703 by [[Simon Fraser, 11th Lord Lovat|Simon Fraser, later Lord Lovat]], to implicate them in a Jacobite plot as part of a personal feud.{{sfn|Lord|2004|p=34}} However, Hooke obtained a letter of support signed by Erroll, the [[James Maule, 4th Earl of Panmure|Earl of Panmure]] and six others, promising 25,000 men, and requesting 8,000 French troops, weapons, money, artillery, ammunition and \u2018majors, lieutenants and serjeants to discipline\u2019 the Scots army.{{sfn|Sinclair-Stevenson|April 1971}}\n\nIn addition, supposed Jacobite Presbyterian [[John Ker]] claimed some [[Cameronian|radical Presbyterians or Cameronians]] supported the Stuarts since 'they are persuaded (Union) will bring an infinite number of calamities upon this nation, and render the Scots slaves to the English.'{{sfn|Sinclair-Stevenson|April 1971}} This was because they viewed union as a threat to Presbyterian [[Church of Scotland]], despite the [[Protestant Religion and Presbyterian Church Act 1707|Protestant Religion and Presbyterian Church Act]].{{sfn|Bowie|2003|p=229}} While the Cameronians were certainly considering this as an option, Ker was a government agent, whose role was to persuade them not to do so.{{sfn|Douglas|2008}}\n\nLouis decided there was enough support to begin planning in November 1707; this was supervised by the [[Louis Ph\u00e9lypeaux, comte de Pontchartrain|Comte de Pontchartrain]], who had been involved with previous attempts in 1692 and 1696. [[Claude de Forbin]] was appointed commander of the naval squadron, with the [[Charles-Auguste de Goyon|Comte de Gac\u00e9]] in charge of the landing force.{{sfn|Sinclair-Stevenson|April 1971}}\n\n==The Expedition==\n[[File:George Byng (1663-1733), 1st Viscount Torrington.jpg|thumb|right|British commander [[George Byng, 1st Viscount Torrington|Sir George Byng]] (1663-1733); ca 1700.]]\nAs the [[Royal Navy]] patrolled exits from the French Channel ports, naval operations often took place during the winter months, when wind and tides made it harder to enforce a blockade. However, it also increased risks from the weather; conditions off North-East Scotland were well-known to French privateers and de Forbin's biggest concern was lack of a confirmed landing place. He later recorded 'the Minister did not mention any port in a condition to receive us, ...or where our fleet might anchor and... troops disembark in safety.'{{sfn|Sinclair-Stevenson|April 1971}}\n\nBased on information supplied by French captains, de Forbin told Pontchartrain and Louis XIV the expedition had no chance of success, but planning continued. The fleet assembled at [[Dunkirk]], a major privateer base for centuries, since ships could reach the [[River Thames|Thames]] in a single tide, allowing them to reach as far north as the [[Orkney|Orkney Islands]].{{sfn|Bromley|1987|p=233}} By the end of February, 5,000 - 6,000 troops were ready to embark, joined by James himself on 9 March.{{sfn|Owen|1938|p=238}}\n\nRather than slow-moving transports, de Forbin insisted on using a larger number of small but fast privateers, many of which reduced their crews and offloaded guns to accommodate the troops. While this improved their chances of avoiding the Royal Navy, they could not hope to defeat them in a naval battle.{{sfn|Owen|1938|p=250}}\n\nThe British had been monitoring French preparations, and a squadron under [[George Byng, 1st Viscount Torrington|Sir George Byng]] now arrived off the nearby port of [[Gravelines]]. This prevented the French departure and since James was ill with measles, the troops were disembarked while he recovered. After a week, Byng returned to port for resupply; James and the soldiers were re-loaded, and on 17 March the French force of 30 privateers and five warships left Dunkirk.{{sfn|Lenman|1980|p=88}}\n[[File:Confiance Kent fight.jpg|thumb|left|Merchant ship (left), battling a much smaller [[privateer]] (right); these small but fast vessels formed the bulk of [[Claude de Forbin]]'s fleet]]\nAlthough their departure was immediately delayed by a two day gale, it forced Byng to take shelter, enabling the French to make for the [[Firth of Forth]]. Rather than following the coastline, de Forbin kept out to sea to avoid being spotted, and ended up north of the proposed landing site. On 25 March, the French anchored near [[Fife Ness]], then spent the next day searching for a landing place, allowing Byng to catch up with them. Despite James' protests, the French privateers could not face the British in battle and headed north; they then spent two days attempting to enter the [[Moray Firth]] before giving up. Most of them made it back to Dunkirk, despite being pursued by the British around the north of Scotland and west of Ireland, but sustained severe damage to both ships and men.{{sfn|Owen|1938|pp=255-263}}\n\nHearing news of the French fleet, some of the Jacobite gentry, including James Stirling of [[Keir House]] and four others, gathered at [[Brig o' Turk]]. They were arrested, imprisoned in [[Newgate Prison]] in London, then later transferred to [[Edinburgh Castle]] where they were tried for [[high treason]].{{sfn|Mitchell|1905|=87}} They were acquitted of this charge, as the evidence against them proved only that they had drunk to James' health.{{sfn|Cobbett|1719|p=1395}}\n\n==Aftermath==\nPerceptions of the expedition's value reflect a fundamental divergence of objectives between France and their Jacobite allies. The Stuarts wanted to regain their throne; for the French, they were a useful, low-cost means of absorbing British resources but a Stuart restoration would not change the threat posed by British expansion.{{sfn|Macinnes |October 1984}}\n\nThe 1708 attempt was a response to the dire military situation France faced as a result of [[John Churchill, 1st Duke of Marlborough|Marlborough's]] victories in [[Flanders]].{{sfn|Szechi|1994|p=56}} It occupied large elements of the British and Dutch navies for several months, with Byng ordered to remain in Scotland even after its defeat, while troops were diverted from Ireland and Southern England. A French army of 110,000 recaptured large parts of the [[Spanish Netherlands]], before defeat at [[Battle of Oudenarde|Oudenarde]] on 11 July evicted them once more.{{sfn|Owen|1938|pp=268-270}} \n\nDespite ultimate defeat, for France the expedition achieved its short-term purpose, but helped the pro-war [[Whigs (British political party)|Whigs]] win a majority in the May [[British general election, 1708|1708 General Election]], the first held after Union. It also damaged the Jacobites, who failed to launch an effective insurgency in Scotland despite popular opposition to Union; in his overview of the political situation, Hooke concluded 'the country seemed to be fully resolved on peace.'{{sfn|Hooke|1760|p=172}} \n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n==Sources==\n* {{cite journal |last1=Bowie |first1=Karin |title=Public Opinion, Popular Politics and the Union of 1707 |journal=The Scottish Historical Review |date=2003 |volume=82 |issue=214 |ref=harv |jstor=25529719}}\n* {{cite book |last1=Bromley |first1=JS |title=Corsairs and Navies, 1600-1760 |date=1987 |publisher=Continnuum-3PL |isbn=978-0907628774 |ref=harv}}\n* {{cite book |last=Cobbett |first=William |author-link=William Cobbett |date=1828 |orig-year=1719 |chapter=The Trials of James Stirling of Keir |editor-last=Howell |editor-first=T B |title=State Trials |publisher=Longman |volume=XIV |ref=harv}}\n* {{cite odnb|id=15549|title=John Ker, of Kersland; 1673-1726 |last=Douglas |first=Hugh|year=2008|ref=harv}}\n* {{cite book |last1=Hooke |first1=Nathaniel |title=Secret History Of Colonel Hoocke's Negotiations In Scotland In Favour Of The Pretender In 1707: Including The Original Letters And Papers Which Passed Versailles And St. Germains |date=1760 |publisher=Nabu |isbn=978-1247343648 |ref=harv |edition=2011}}\n* {{cite odnb|id=3827|title=Buchan, Thomas; 1641-1724  |last=Hopkins |first=Paul|year=2004 |ref=harv}}\n* {{cite book|last1=Lenman|first1=Bruce|title=The Jacobite risings in Britain 1689-1746|date=1980|publisher=Eyre Methuen|location=London|isbn=978-0413396501|ref=harv}}\n* {{cite book |last1=Lord |first1=Evelyn |title=The Stuarts' Secret Army |date=2004 |publisher=Pearson |isbn=978-0582772564 |ref=harv}}\n* {{cite journal |title=Lord High Admiral's Answer to the Report of the Committee, upon the Petition of the Merchants complaining of Losses for Want of Cruiz rs and Convoys |journal=Journal of the House of Lords |date=1708 |volume=18 |ref=harv|url=http://www.british-history.ac.uk/lords-jrnl/vol18/pp405-423 |accessdate=16 September 2018|ref={{harvid||Journal of the House of Lords|1708}}}}\n* {{cite journal |last1=Macinnes |first1=AI |title=Jacobitism |journal=History Today |date=October 1984 |volume=34 |issue=10 |url=https://www.historytoday.com/ai-maccines/jacobitism|ref=harv}}\n* {{cite book |last=Mitchell |first=John Oswald |date=1905 |title=Old Glasgow essays|publisher=J Maclehose |ref=harv}}\n* {{cite book |last1=Owen |first1=John Hely |title=War at Sea Under Queen Anne 1702-1708 |date=1938 |publisher=Cambridge University Press |isbn=978-1108013383 |ref=harv |edition=2010}}\n* {{cite journal |last1=Sinclair-Stevenson |first1=Christopher |title=The Jacobite Expedition of 1708 |journal=History Today |date=April 1971 |volume=21 |issue=4 |ref=harv}}\n* {{cite book|last1=Szechi|first1=Daniel|title= The Jacobites: Britain and Europe, 1688-1788|date=1994|publisher=Manchester University Press|isbn=978-0719037740|ref=harv}}\n* {{cite book |last1=Whatley |first1=Christopher |title=Scottish Society, 1707-1830: Beyond Jacobitism, Towards Industrialisation |date=2011 |publisher=Manchester University Press |isbn=978-0719045400 |ref=harv}};\n* {{cite book |last1=Williams |first1=Neville E |title=The Eighteenth-Century Constitution 1688-1815: Documents and Commentary |date=1960 |publisher=Cambridge University Press |isbn=9780521091237 |ref=harv |edition=2009}}\n\n{{Jacobitism}}\n\n[[Category:Cancelled military operations involving France]]\n[[Category:Battles of the War of the Spanish Succession]]\n[[Category:1708 in Great Britain]]\n[[Category:1708 in France]]\n[[Category:Cancelled invasions]]\n[[Category:Invasions of the United Kingdom]]\n[[Category:Invasions by France|Britain 1708]]\n", "text_old": "{{Infobox military conflict\n| conflict    = Planned French Invasion of Britain, 1708\n| partof      = [[Jacobite risings]]\n| image       = File:Jacobite broadside - Coloured portrait of Prince James as young man1.jpg\n| image_size  = 225px\n| caption     = [[James Francis Edward Stuart]] ca 1708\n| date        = March 1708\n| place       = Great Britain\n| result      = Decisive British government victory\n| combatant1  = [[Jacobitism|Jacobites]] <br /> {{flagcountry|Kingdom of France}}\n| combatant2  = {{flagcountry|Kingdom of Great Britain}}\n| commander1  = {{flagicon|Kingdom of France}}[[Claude de Forbin]]<br /> {{flagicon|Kingdom of France}} [[Charles-Auguste de Goyon|Comte de Gac\u00e9]]\n| commander2  = {{flagicon|Kingdom of Great Britain}} [[George Byng, 1st Viscount Torrington|Sir George Byng]] <br /> {{flagicon|Kingdom of Great Britain}} Rear Admiral Baker\n| campaignbox={{Campaignbox Jacobite risings}}\n}}\nThe '''Planned French Invasion of Britain, 1708,''' also known as the ''''Entreprise d\u2019\u00c9cosse,'''' took place during the [[War of the Spanish Succession]]. The French planned to land 5,000-6,000 soldiers in North-East [[Scotland]] to support a rising by local [[Jacobitism|Jacobites]], that would restore [[James Francis Edward Stuart]] to the throne of Great Britain. \n\nDespite French commander [[Claude de Forbin]] warning the chances of evading the [[Royal Navy]] long enough to land his troops were extremely limited, his fleet of small [[privateers]] reached Scotland in March 1708. As he had forecast, he was unable to disembark the troops and returned home, narrowly escaping a pursuing British naval force.\n\nSuch attempts reflected a fundamental and continuing divergence of objectives; while the Stuarts wanted to regain their throne, for the French, they were a simple and low-cost way to absorb British resources. Much of the [[Royal Navy]] was occupied chasing de Forbin, while troops were diverted from Ireland and Southern England. This made it successful for France, but a failure for the Jacobites. \n\n==Background==\n{{Main|War of the Spanish Succession}}\n[[File:Claude de Forbin.jpg|thumb|left|French Admiral [[Claude de Forbin]] (1656-1733); he had little faith in the expedition from the start]]\nUnder the 1697 [[Treaty of Ryswick]], [[Louis XIV]] withdrew support from the exiled [[James II]], and recognised [[William III of England|William III]] as legitimate monarch. However, when James died on 16 September 1701, he reneged on this, and proclaimed his son [[James Francis Edward Stuart]] King of England and Scotland. The [[War of the Spanish Succession]] began soon after; William died in March 1702 and was succeeded by the last Stuart monarch, James' Protestant daughter [[Anne, Queen of Great Britain|Anne]].{{sfn|Williams|1960|p=340}}\n\nBy the end of 1707, the war had reached stalemate; despite victories in [[Flanders]], the Allies had been unable to break French border defences, or place their candidate on the Spanish throne. Both sides attempted to use internal conflicts to break the deadlock; Britain supported the [[Camisard|Camisard rebels]] in South-West France, with the Jacobites serving a similar function for the French.{{sfn|Owen|1938|p=238}}\n\nJacobite agent [[Nathaniel Hooke (Jacobite)|Nathaniel Hooke]] convinced Louis there was an opportunity for a Scottish rising, which would divert British troops from Europe. The [[Acts of Union 1707|1707 Act of Union]] was widely unpopular in Scotland, while French [[privateer]]s caused enormous losses for their maritime trade, and the coastal fishing industry.{{sfn|Whatley|2011|p=55}} Protecting Scottish shipping was not a priority for the [[Royal Navy]], which faced multiple demands on its resources for escorting merchant convoys.{{sfn|Journal of the House of Lords|1708|pp=405\u2013423}}\n\nHooke visited Scotland in 1707, meeting supporters like the [[Charles Hay, 13th Earl of Erroll|Earl of Erroll]], while elderly Jacobite [[Thomas Buchan]] provided reports on bases at [[Fort William, Highland|Fort William]] and [[Inverness]].{{sfn|Hopkins|2004}} Senior nobles like the Dukes of [[John_Murray,_1st_Duke_of_Atholl|Atholl]] and [[James Hamilton, 4th Duke of Hamilton|Hamilton]] refused to commit, partly due to an attempt in 1703 by [[Simon Fraser, 11th Lord Lovat|Simon Fraser, later Lord Lovat]], to implicate them in a Jacobite plot as part of a personal feud.{{sfn|Lord|2004|p=34}} However, Hooke obtained a letter of support signed by Erroll, the [[James Maule, 4th Earl of Panmure|Earl of Panmure]] and six others, promising 25,000 men, and requesting 8,000 French troops, weapons, money, artillery, ammunition and \u2018majors, lieutenants and serjeants to discipline\u2019 the Scots army.{{sfn|Sinclair-Stevenson|April 1971}}\n\nIn addition, supposed Jacobite Presbyterian [[John Ker]] claimed some [[Cameronian|radical Presbyterians or Cameronians]] supported the Stuarts since 'they are persuaded (Union) will bring an infinite number of calamities upon this nation, and render the Scots slaves to the English.'{{sfn|Sinclair-Stevenson|April 1971}} This was because they viewed union as a threat to Presbyterian [[Church of Scotland]], despite the [[Protestant Religion and Presbyterian Church Act 1707|Protestant Religion and Presbyterian Church Act]].{{sfn|Bowie|2003|p=229}} While the Cameronians were certainly considering this as an option, Ker was a government agent, whose role was to persuade them not to do so.{{sfn|Douglas|2008}}\n\nLouis decided there was enough support to begin planning in November 1707; this was supervised by the [[Louis Ph\u00e9lypeaux, comte de Pontchartrain|Comte de Pontchartrain]], who had been involved with previous attempts in 1692 and 1696. [[Claude de Forbin]] was appointed commander of the naval squadron, with the [[Charles-Auguste de Goyon|Comte de Gac\u00e9]] in charge of the landing force.{{sfn|Sinclair-Stevenson|April 1971}}\n\n==The Expedition==\n[[File:George Byng (1663-1733), 1st Viscount Torrington.jpg|thumb|right|British commander [[George Byng, 1st Viscount Torrington|Sir George Byng]] (1663-1733); ca 1700.]]\nAs the [[Royal Navy]] patrolled exits from the French Channel ports, naval operations often took place during the winter months, when wind and tides made it harder to enforce a blockade. However, it also increased risks from the weather; conditions off North-East Scotland were well-known to French privateers and de Forbin's biggest concern was lack of a confirmed landing place. He later recorded 'the Minister did not mention any port in a condition to receive us, ...or where our fleet might anchor and... troops disembark in safety.'{{sfn|Sinclair-Stevenson|April 1971}}\n\nBased on information supplied by French captains, de Forbin told Pontchartrain and Louis XIV the expedition had no chance of success, but planning continued. The fleet assembled at [[Dunkirk]], a major privateer base for centuries, since ships could reach the [[River Thames|Thames]] in a single tide, allowing them to reach as far north as the [[Orkney|Orkney Islands]].{{sfn|Bromley|1987|p=233}} By the end of February, 5,000 - 6,000 troops were ready to embark, joined by James himself on 9 March.{{sfn|Owen|1938|p=238}}\n\nRather than slow-moving transports, de Forbin insisted on using a larger number of small but fast privateers, many of which reduced their crews and offloaded guns to accommodate the troops. While this improved their chances of avoiding the Royal Navy, they could not hope to defeat them in a naval battle.{{sfn|Owen|1938|p=250}}\n\nThe British had been monitoring French preparations, and a squadron under [[George Byng, 1st Viscount Torrington|Sir George Byng]] now arrived off the nearby port of [[Gravelines]]. This prevented the French departure and since James was ill with measles, the troops were disembarked while he recovered. After a week, Byng returned to port for resupply; James and the soldiers were re-loaded, and on 17 March the French force of 30 privateers and five warships left Dunkirk.{{sfn|Lenman|1980|p=88}}\n[[File:Confiance Kent fight.jpg|thumb|left|Merchant ship (left), battling a much smaller [[privateer]] (right); these small but fast vessels formed the bulk of [[Claude de Forbin]]'s fleet]]\nAlthough their departure was immediately delayed by a two day gale, it forced Byng to take shelter, enabling the French to make for the [[Firth of Forth]]. Rather than following the coastline, de Forbin kept out to sea to avoid being spotted, and ended up north of the proposed landing site. On 25 March, the French anchored near [[Fife Ness]], then spent the next day searching for a landing place, allowing Byng to catch up with them. Despite James' protests, the French privateers could not face the British in battle and headed north; they then spent two days attempting to enter the [[Moray Firth]] before giving up. Most of them made it back to Dunkirk, despite being pursued by the British around the north of Scotland and west of Ireland, but sustained severe damage to both ships and men.{{sfn|Owen|1938|pp=255-263}}\n\nHearing news of the French fleet, some of the Jacobite gentry, including James Stirling of [[Keir House]] and four others, gathered at [[Brig o' Turk]]. They were arrested, imprisoned in [[Newgate Prison]] in London, then later transferred to [[Edinburgh Castle]] where they were tried for [[high treason]].{{sfn|Mitchell|1905|=87}} They were acquitted of this charge, as the evidence against them proved only that they had drunk to James' health.{{sfn|Cobbett|1719|p=1395}}\n\n==Aftermath==\nPerceptions of the expedition's value reflect a fundamental divergence of objectives between France and their Jacobite allies. The Stuarts wanted to regain their throne; for the French, they were a useful, low-cost means of absorbing British resources but a Stuart restoration would not change the threat posed by British expansion.{{sfn|Macinnes |October 1984}}\n\nThe 1708 attempt was a response to the dire military situation France faced as a result of [[John Churchill, 1st Duke of Marlborough|Marlborough's]] victories in [[Flanders]].{{sfn|Szechi|1994|p=56}} It occupied large elements of the British and Dutch navies for several months, with Byng ordered to remain in Scotland even after its defeat, while troops were diverted from Ireland and Southern England. A French army of 110,000 recaptured large parts of the [[Spanish Netherlands]], before defeat at [[Battle of Oudenarde|Oudenarde]] on 11 July evicted them once more.{{sfn|Owen|1938|pp=268-270}} \n\nDespite ultimate defeat, for France the expedition achieved its short-term purpose, but helped the pro-war [[Whigs (British political party)|Whigs]] win a majority in the May [[British general election, 1708|1708 General Election]], the first held after Union. It also damaged the Jacobites, who failed to launch an effective insurgency in Scotland despite popular opposition to Union; in his overview of the political situation, Hooke concluded 'the country seemed to be fully resolved on peace.'{{sfn|Hooke|1760|p=172}} \n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n==Sources==\n* {{cite journal |last1=Bowie |first1=Karin |title=Public Opinion, Popular Politics and the Union of 1707 |journal=The Scottish Historical Review |date=2003 |volume=82 |issue=214 |ref=harv |jstor=25529719}}\n* {{cite book |last1=Bromley |first1=JS |title=Corsairs and Navies, 1600-1760 |date=1987 |publisher=Continnuum-3PL |isbn=978-0907628774 |ref=harv}}\n* {{cite book |last=Cobbett |first=William |author-link=William Cobbett |date=1828 |orig-year=1719 |chapter=The Trials of James Stirling of Keir |editor-last=Howell |editor-first=T B |title=State Trials |publisher=Longman |volume=XIV |ref=harv}}\n* {{cite odnb|id=15549|title=John Ker, of Kersland; 1673-1726 |last=Douglas |first=Hugh|year=2008|ref=harv}}\n* {{cite book |last1=Hooke |first1=Nathaniel |title=Secret History Of Colonel Hoocke's Negotiations In Scotland In Favour Of The Pretender In 1707: Including The Original Letters And Papers Which Passed Versailles And St. Germains |date=1760 |publisher=Nabu |isbn=978-1247343648 |ref=harv |edition=2011}}\n* {{cite odnb|id=3827|title=Buchan, Thomas; 1641-1724  |last=Hopkins |first=Paul|year=2004 |ref=harv}}\n* {{cite book|last1=Lenman|first1=Bruce|title=The Jacobite risings in Britain 1689-1746|date=1980|publisher=Eyre Methuen|location=London|isbn=978-0413396501|ref=harv}}\n* {{cite book |last1=Lord |first1=Evelyn |title=The Stuarts' Secret Army |date=2004 |publisher=Pearson |isbn=978-0582772564 |ref=harv}}\n* {{cite journal |title=Lord High Admiral's Answer to the Report of the Committee, upon the Petition of the Merchants complaining of Losses for Want of Cruiz rs and Convoys |journal=Journal of the House of Lords |date=1708 |volume=18 |ref=harv|url=http://www.british-history.ac.uk/lords-jrnl/vol18/pp405-423 |accessdate=16 September 2018}}\n* {{cite journal |last1=Macinnes |first1=AI |title=Jacobitism |journal=History Today |date=October 1984 |volume=34 |issue=10 |url=https://www.historytoday.com/ai-maccines/jacobitism|ref=harv}}\n* {{cite book |last=Mitchell |first=John Oswald |date=1905 |title=Old Glasgow essays|publisher=J Maclehose |ref=harv}}\n* {{cite book |last1=Owen |first1=John Hely |title=War at Sea Under Queen Anne 1702-1708 |date=1938 |publisher=Cambridge University Press |isbn=978-1108013383 |ref=harv |edition=2010}}\n* {{cite journal |last1=Sinclair-Stevenson |first1=Christopher |title=The Jacobite Expedition of 1708 |journal=History Today |date=April 1971 |volume=21 |issue=4 |ref=harv}}\n* {{cite book|last1=Szechi|first1=Daniel|title= The Jacobites: Britain and Europe, 1688-1788|date=1994|publisher=Manchester University Press|isbn=978-0719037740|ref=harv}}\n* {{cite book |last1=Whatley |first1=Christopher |title=Scottish Society, 1707-1830: Beyond Jacobitism, Towards Industrialisation |date=2011 |publisher=Manchester University Press |isbn=978-0719045400 |ref=harv}};\n* {{cite book |last1=Williams |first1=Neville E |title=The Eighteenth-Century Constitution 1688-1815: Documents and Commentary |date=1960 |publisher=Cambridge University Press |isbn=9780521091237 |ref=harv |edition=2009}}\n\n{{Jacobitism}}\n\n[[Category:Cancelled military operations involving France]]\n[[Category:Battles of the War of the Spanish Succession]]\n[[Category:1708 in Great Britain]]\n[[Category:1708 in France]]\n[[Category:Cancelled invasions]]\n[[Category:Invasions of the United Kingdom]]\n[[Category:Invasions by France|Britain 1708]]\n", "name_user": "Eddie891", "label": "safe", "comment": "fix one harv ref", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Planned_French_invasion_of_Britain_(1708)"}
{"title_page": "Aplysina cavernicola", "text_new": "{{Speciesbox\n| image         = Gelber Schwamm an der S\u00fcdk\u00fcste von Mykonos.jpg\n| image_caption = A cool thing.[[Mykonos|Mykonos, Greece]]\n| taxon         = Aplysina cavernicola\n| authority = (Vacelet, 1959)<ref name=WoRMS>{{cite WoRMS |author=van Soest, Rob W.M. |year=2020 |title=''Aplysina cavernicola'' (Vacelet, 1959) |id=133913 |accessdate=19 February 2020}}</ref>\n| synonyms      = \n* ''Verongia cavernicola'' <small>Vacelet, 1959</small>\n}}\n\n'''''Aplysina cavernicola''''' is a species of [[starfish]] in the family [[Aplysinidae]]. It is native to the [[Mediterranean Sea]] where it grows in caves and under overhangs.<ref name=DORIS>{{cite web |url=https://doris.ffessm.fr/index.php/Especes/Aplysina-cavernicola-Eponge-cavernicole-jaune-631 |title=''Aplysina cavernicola'' (Vacelet, 1959) |language=French |publisher=DORIS |accessdate=19 February 2020}}</ref>\n\n==Description==\n''Aplysina cavernicola'' forms clumps that may be up to {{convert|30|cm|in|0|abbr=on}} across. It has a base that adheres to a rock or other hard surface, out of which project a number of finger-like processes up to {{convert|6|cm|in|1|abbr=on}} long and {{convert|2|cm|in|1|abbr=on}} in diameter. The surface is sparsely covered with small conical protrusions, which are caused by the tips of horny fibres embedded in the tissues. There are no [[Sponge spicule|spicules]], structural support being provided by a mesh of [[spongin]] fibres. Water is drawn in through pores known as [[Ostium (sponges)|ostia]] at the base of the sponge and ejected from the [[osculum|oscuili]] which are situated in slight depressions at the tips of the processes. The body colour is yellowish.<ref name=DORIS/>\n\n==Ecology==\nThis sponge is a [[hermaphrodite]]; ciliated larvae known as [[parenchymella]] larvae are released into the water and soon settle in a suitable location and undergo [[metamorphosis]] into juvenile sponges.<ref name=Ruppert>{{cite book |title=Invertebrate Zoology, 7th edition |last1=Ruppert |first1=Edward E. |last2=Fox |first2=Richard, S. |last3=Barnes |first3=Robert D. |last-author-amp=yes |year=2004 |publisher=Cengage Learning |isbn=978-81-315-0104-7 |page=87 }}</ref>\n\nThis sponge accumulates brominated [[isoxazoline]] [[alkaloid]]s in its tissues at concentrations up to 10% of its dry body weight. By incorporating these  biologically active compounds into experimental diets, it has been shown in feeding trials that they are distasteful to the [[sphinx blenny]] (''Blennius sphinx''), a [[List of feeding behaviours#By food type|polyphagous]] Mediterranean fish, while other sponges are readily eaten. Certain metabolic derivatives of these isoxazolines, such as [[dienone]] and [[aeroplysinin]], are not distasteful to the fish, but may have anti-microbial properties that protect the sponge from [[bacteria]]l [[pathogen]]s.<ref>{{cite journal |author=Thoms, Carsten; Wolff, Matthias; Padmarkumar, K.; Ebel, Rainer; Proksch, Peter |year=2004 |title=Chemical Defense of Mediterranean Sponges ''Aplysina cavernicola'' and ''Aplysina aerophoba'' |journal=Zeitschrift f\u00fcr Naturforschung C |volume=59 |issue=1\u20132 |pages=113\u2013122 |doi=10.1515/znc-2004-1-222 |pmid=15018063 }}</ref> This sponge also bioaccumulates [[radionuclide]]s, and has been used as a [[model organism]] to study the presence of isotopes such as [[americium-241]] in seawater.<ref>{{cite journal |author=Maloubier, Melody; Michel, Herv\u00e9; Solari, Pier Lorenzo; Moisy, Philippe; Tribalat, Marie-Aude; Oberhaensli, Fran\u00e7ois R.; Bottein, Marie Yasmine Dechraoui; Thomas, Olivier P.; Monfort, Marguerite; Moulin, Christophe; Den Auwer, Christophe |year=2015 |title=Speciation of americium in seawater and accumulation in the marine sponge ''Aplysina cavernicola'' |journal=Dalton Transactions |volume=44 |issue=47 |pages=20584\u201320596 |doi=10.1039/C5DT02805A |pmid=26556307 }}</ref>\n\n==References==\n{{Commons category}}\n{{Wikispecies}}\n{{Reflist}}\n{{Taxonbar|from=Q1891651}}\n\n[[Category:Animals described in 1875]]\n[[Category:Verongimorpha]]\n", "text_old": "{{Speciesbox\n| image         = Gelber Schwamm an der S\u00fcdk\u00fcste von Mykonos.jpg\n| image_caption = A colony off the coast of [[Mykonos|Mykonos, Greece]]\n| taxon         = Aplysina cavernicola\n| authority = (Vacelet, 1959)<ref name=WoRMS>{{cite WoRMS |author=van Soest, Rob W.M. |year=2020 |title=''Aplysina cavernicola'' (Vacelet, 1959) |id=133913 |accessdate=19 February 2020}}</ref>\n| synonyms      = \n* ''Verongia cavernicola'' <small>Vacelet, 1959</small>\n}}\n\n'''''Aplysina cavernicola''''' is a species of [[sponge]] in the family [[Aplysinidae]]. It is native to the [[Mediterranean Sea]] where it grows in caves and under overhangs.<ref name=DORIS>{{cite web |url=https://doris.ffessm.fr/index.php/Especes/Aplysina-cavernicola-Eponge-cavernicole-jaune-631 |title=''Aplysina cavernicola'' (Vacelet, 1959) |language=French |publisher=DORIS |accessdate=19 February 2020}}</ref>\n\n==Description==\n''Aplysina cavernicola'' forms clumps that may be up to {{convert|30|cm|in|0|abbr=on}} across. It has a base that adheres to a rock or other hard surface, out of which project a number of finger-like processes up to {{convert|6|cm|in|1|abbr=on}} long and {{convert|2|cm|in|1|abbr=on}} in diameter. The surface is sparsely covered with small conical protrusions, which are caused by the tips of horny fibres embedded in the tissues. There are no [[Sponge spicule|spicules]], structural support being provided by a mesh of [[spongin]] fibres. Water is drawn in through pores known as [[Ostium (sponges)|ostia]] at the base of the sponge and ejected from the [[osculum|oscuili]] which are situated in slight depressions at the tips of the processes. The body colour is yellowish.<ref name=DORIS/>\n\n==Ecology==\nThis sponge is a [[hermaphrodite]]; ciliated larvae known as [[parenchymella]] larvae are released into the water and soon settle in a suitable location and undergo [[metamorphosis]] into juvenile sponges.<ref name=Ruppert>{{cite book |title=Invertebrate Zoology, 7th edition |last1=Ruppert |first1=Edward E. |last2=Fox |first2=Richard, S. |last3=Barnes |first3=Robert D. |last-author-amp=yes |year=2004 |publisher=Cengage Learning |isbn=978-81-315-0104-7 |page=87 }}</ref>\n\nThis sponge accumulates brominated [[isoxazoline]] [[alkaloid]]s in its tissues at concentrations up to 10% of its dry body weight. By incorporating these  biologically active compounds into experimental diets, it has been shown in feeding trials that they are distasteful to the [[sphinx blenny]] (''Blennius sphinx''), a [[List of feeding behaviours#By food type|polyphagous]] Mediterranean fish, while other sponges are readily eaten. Certain metabolic derivatives of these isoxazolines, such as [[dienone]] and [[aeroplysinin]], are not distasteful to the fish, but may have anti-microbial properties that protect the sponge from [[bacteria]]l [[pathogen]]s.<ref>{{cite journal |author=Thoms, Carsten; Wolff, Matthias; Padmarkumar, K.; Ebel, Rainer; Proksch, Peter |year=2004 |title=Chemical Defense of Mediterranean Sponges ''Aplysina cavernicola'' and ''Aplysina aerophoba'' |journal=Zeitschrift f\u00fcr Naturforschung C |volume=59 |issue=1\u20132 |pages=113\u2013122 |doi=10.1515/znc-2004-1-222 |pmid=15018063 }}</ref> This sponge also bioaccumulates [[radionuclide]]s, and has been used as a [[model organism]] to study the presence of isotopes such as [[americium-241]] in seawater.<ref>{{cite journal |author=Maloubier, Melody; Michel, Herv\u00e9; Solari, Pier Lorenzo; Moisy, Philippe; Tribalat, Marie-Aude; Oberhaensli, Fran\u00e7ois R.; Bottein, Marie Yasmine Dechraoui; Thomas, Olivier P.; Monfort, Marguerite; Moulin, Christophe; Den Auwer, Christophe |year=2015 |title=Speciation of americium in seawater and accumulation in the marine sponge ''Aplysina cavernicola'' |journal=Dalton Transactions |volume=44 |issue=47 |pages=20584\u201320596 |doi=10.1039/C5DT02805A |pmid=26556307 }}</ref>\n\n==References==\n{{Commons category}}\n{{Wikispecies}}\n{{Reflist}}\n{{Taxonbar|from=Q1891651}}\n\n[[Category:Animals described in 1875]]\n[[Category:Verongimorpha]]\n", "name_user": "75.136.127.11", "label": "unsafe", "comment": "", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Aplysina_cavernicola"}
